6. What is the function of adipocytes?
That’s right! Adipocyte stores triglycerides in a single, large lipid droplets within the cell.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
This is a section through the quadriceps femoris and its neurovascular bundle. It demonstrates the role of adipose tissue as the “Styrofoam packing chips of the human body”.

Adipose tissue composes mostly of adipocytes by volume, in a delicate reticular fibre stroma; very vascularized. 
Adipocyte stores triglycerides in a single, large lipid droplet that occupies most of the cell. The cell nucleus is pushed off to the periphery of the cell by the lipid droplet. The cells appear to be emptied as lipids are extracted during tissue processing. 
Adipose tissue acts as a energy depot, thermal insulator and shock absorber. It is usually found with areolar CT.  The amount and distribution varies with age, sex, nutrition & activity level. It is particularly abundant deep to skin, behind eyes, around kidneys
